Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, Anglie","Avranches, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Francie","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Francie"},"da":{"13 October 1025–23 Jul 1082":"19. oktober 1025–29. juli 1082","1025–1082":"1025–1082","1035–1103":"1035–1103","1050–Female":"1050–Afdød","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1050–1109":"1050–1109","0989–1041":"0989–1041","1066":"1066","1041":"1041","1050":"1050","1082":"1082","13 October 1025":"19. oktober 1025","1103":"1103","1025":"1025","1101":"1101","1035":"1035","after 1041":"efter 1041","23 Jul 1082":"29. juli 1082","0989":"0989","19 August 1050":"19. august 1050","1109":"1109","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Avranches, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Frankrig","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"13 October 1025–23 Jul 1082":"19 oktober 1025–29 juli 1082","1025–1082":"1025–1082","1035–1103":"1035–1103","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1050–1109":"1050–1109","0989–1041":"0989–1041","1066":"1066","1041":"1041","1050":"1050","1082":"1082","13 October 1025":"19 oktober 1025","1103":"1103","1025":"1025","1101":"1101","1035":"1035","after 1041":"na 1041","23 Jul 1082":"29 juli 1082","0989":"0989","19 August 1050":"19 augustus 1050","1109":"1109","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Avranches, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"13 October 1025–23 Jul 1082":"19 October 1025–29 July 1082","1025–1082":"1025–1082","1035–1103":"1035–1103","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1050–1101":"1050–1101","1050–1109":"1050–1109","0989–1041":"0989–1041","1066":"1066","1041":"1041","1050":"1050","1082":"1082","13 October 1025":"19 October 1025","1103":"1103","1025":"1025","1101":"1101","1035":"1035","after 1041":"after 1041","23 Jul 1082":"29 July 1082","0989":"0989","19 August 1050":"19 August 1050","1109":"1109","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Avranches, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France","Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gros","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name, possibly derived from Norse <i>gróa</i> ‘to grow’, or possibly related to the Celtic element <i>gruach</i> ‘woman’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Goz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Ros  , with the final consonant altered to represent the voiced sound of the names from which it derives."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":9,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":40,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Le Gros Goz Viscount Avranches was born on 19 October 1025, in Avranches, Manche, Normandy, France as the son of Thurstan Le Goz Vicomte d'Avranches. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Emma de Conteville. He died on 29 July 1082, in Hastings, Sussex, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"13 October 1025–23 Jul 1082":"19. oktoober 1025–29. juuli 1082","1025–1082":"1025–1082","1035–1